# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: genetic-engineering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting generally follows three steps: pre-bioprinting, bioprinting, and post-bioprinting.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Pre-bioprinting is the process of creating a model that the printer will later create and choosing the materials that will be used.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] One of the first steps is to obtain a biopsy of the organ, to sample cells.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Common technologies used for bioprinting are computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] To print with a layer-by-layer approach, tomographic reconstruction is done on the images.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The now-2D images are then sent to the printer to be made.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Once the image is created, certain cells are isolated and multiplied.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] These cells are then mixed with a special liquefied material that provides oxygen and other nutrients to keep them alive.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] This aggregation of cells does not require a scaffold, and is required for placing in the tubular-like tissue fusion for processes such as extrusion.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In the second step, the liquid mixtures of cells, matrix, and nutrients known as bioinks are placed in a printer cartridge and deposited using the patients' medical scans.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] When a bioprinted pre-tissue is transferred to an incubator, this cell-based pre-tissue matures into a tissue.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting for fabricating biological constructs typically involves dispensing cells onto a biocompatible scaffold using a successive layer-by-layer approach to generate tissue-like three-dimensional structures.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Artificial organs such as livers and kidneys made by 3D bioprinting have been shown to lack crucial elements that affect the body such as working blood vessels, tubules for collecting urine, and the growth of billions of cells required for these organs.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Without these components the body has no way to get the essential nutrients and oxygen deep within their interiors.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Given that every tissue in the body is naturally composed of different cell types, many technologies for printing these cells vary in their ability to ensure stability and viability of the cells during the manufacturing process.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Some of the methods that are used for 3D bioprinting of cells are photolithography, magnetic 3D bioprinting, stereolithography, and direct cell extrusion.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The post-bioprinting process is necessary to create a stable structure from the biological material.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] If this process is not well-maintained, the mechanical integrity and function of the 3D printed object is at risk.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] To maintain the object, both mechanical and chemical stimulations are needed.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] These stimulations send signals to the cells to control the remodeling and growth of tissues.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In addition, in recent development, bioreactor technologies have allowed the rapid maturation of tissues, vascularization of tissues and the ability to survive transplants.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Bioreactors work in either providing convective nutrient transport, creating microgravity environments, changing the pressure causing solution to flow through the cells, or adding compression for dynamic or static loading.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Each type of bioreactor is ideal for different types of tissue, for example compression bioreactors are ideal for cartilage tissue.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Researchers in the field have developed approaches to produce living organs that are constructed with the appropriate biological and mechanical properties.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting is based on three main approaches: biomimicry, autonomous self-assembly and mini-tissue building blocks.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The first approach of bioprinting is called biomimicry.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The main goal of this approach is to create fabricated structures that are identical to the natural structure that are found in the tissues and organs in the human body.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Biomimicry requires duplication of the shape, framework, and the microenvironment of the organs and tissues.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The application of biomimicry in bioprinting involves creating both identical cellular and extracellular parts of organs.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] For this approach to be successful, the tissues must be replicated on a micro scale.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Therefore, it is necessary to understand the microenvironment, the nature of the biological forces in this microenvironment, the precise organization of functional and supporting cell types, solubility factors, and the composition of extracellular matrix.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The second approach of bioprinting is autonomous self-assembly.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] This approach relies on the physical process of embryonic organ development as a model to replicate the tissues of interest.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] When cells are in their early development, they create their own extracellular matrix building block, the proper cell signaling, and independent arrangement and patterning to provide the required biological functions and micro-architecture.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Autonomous self-assembly demands specific information about the developmental techniques of the tissues and organs of the embryo.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] There is a "scaffold-free" model that uses self-assembling spheroids that subjects to fusion and cell arrangement to resemble evolving tissues.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Autonomous self-assembly depends on the cell as the fundamental driver of histogenesis, guiding the building blocks, structural and functional properties of these tissues.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] It demands a deeper understanding of how embryonic tissues mechanisms develop as well as the microenvironment surrounded to create the bioprinted tissues.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The third approach of bioprinting is a combination of both the biomimicry and self-assembly approaches, called mini tissues.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Organs and tissues are built from very small functional components.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The mini-tissue approach takes these small pieces and arrange them into larger framework.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Akin to ordinary ink printers, bioprinters have three major components to them.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] These are the hardware used, the type of bio-ink, and the material it is printed on (biomaterials).
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Bio-ink is a material made from living cells that behaves much like a liquid, allowing people to 'print' it in order to create the desired shape.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] To make bio-ink, scientists create a slurry of cells that can be loaded into a cartridge and inserted into a specially designed printer, along with another cartridge containing a gel known as bio-paper.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In bioprinting, there are three major types of printers that have been used.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] These are inkjet, laser-assisted, and extrusion printers.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Inkjet printers are mainly used in bioprinting for fast and large-scale products.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] One type of inkjet printer, called drop-on-demand inkjet printer, prints materials in exact amounts, minimizing cost and waste.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Printers that use lasers provide high-resolution printing; however, these printers are often expensive.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Extrusion printers print cells layer-by-layer, just like 3D printing to create 3D constructs.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In addition to just cells, extrusion printers may also use hydrogels infused with cells.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Extrusion-based printing is a very common technique within the field of 3D printing which entails extruding, or forcing, a continuous stream of melted solid material or viscous liquid through a sort of orifice, often a nozzle or syringe.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] When it comes to extrusion based bioprinting, there are four main types of extrusion.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] These are pneumatic driven, piston driven, screw driven and eccentric screw driven (also known as progressing cavity pump).
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Each extrusion method has their own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Pneumatic extrusion uses pressurized air to force liquid bioink through a depositing agent.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Air filters are commonly used to sterilize the air before it is used, to ensure air pushing the bioink is not contaminated.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Piston driven extrusion uses a piston connected to a guide screw.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The linear motion of the piston squeezes material out of the nozzle.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Screw driven extrusion uses an auger screw to extrude material using rotational motion.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Screw driven devices allow for the use of higher viscosity materials and provide more volumetric control.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Eccentric screw driven systems allow for a much more precise deposition of low to high viscosity materials due to the self-sealing chambers in the extruder.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Once printed, many materials require a crosslinking step to achieve the desired mechanical properties for the construct, which can be achieved for example with the treatment of chemical agents or photo-crosslinkers.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Direct extrusion is one of the most common extrusion-based bioprinting techniques, wherein the pressurized force directs the bioink to flow out of the nozzle, and directly print the scaffold without any necessary casting.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The bioink itself for this approach can be a blend of polymer hydrogels, naturally derived materials such as collagen, and live cells suspended in the solution.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In this manner, scaffolds can be cultured post-print and without the need for further treatment for cellular seeding.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Some focus in the use of direct printing techniques is based upon the use of coaxial nozzle assemblies, or coaxial extrusion.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The coaxial nozzle setup enables the simultaneous extrusion of multiple material bioinks, capable of making multi-layered scaffolds in a single extrusion step.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The development of tubular structures has found the layered extrusion achieved via these techniques desirable for the radial variability in material characterization that it can offer, as the coaxial nozzle provides an inner and outer tube for bioink flow.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Indirect extrusion techniques for bioprinting rather require the printing of a base material of cell-laden hydrogels, but unlike direct extrusion contains a sacrificial hydrogel that can be trivially removed post-printing through thermal or chemical extraction.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The remaining resin solidifies and becomes the desired 3D-printed construct.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Laser-based bioprinting can be split into two major classes: those based on cell transfer technologies or photo-polymerization.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In cell transfer laser printing, a laser stimulates the connection between energy-absorbing material (e.g. gold, titanium, etc.) and the bioink.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] This 'donor layer' vaporizes under the laser's irradiation, forming a bubble from the bioink layer which gets deposited from a jet.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Photo-polymerization techniques rather use photoinitiated reactions to solidify the ink, moving the beam path of a laser to induce the formation of a desired construct.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Certain laser frequencies paired with photopolymerization reactions can be carried out without damaging cells in the material.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In this form of printing, plastic residues are melted down and individual layered in sections to create a desired shape.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Nylon and PVA are examples of biomaterials used in this method.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] This technique is most often used to design prototypes for prosthetics and cartilage construction.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Another form of bioprinting involves an inkjet printer, which is primarily used in biomedical settings.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] This method prints detailed proteins and nucleic acids.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Hydrogels are commonly selected as the bioink.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Cells can be printed on to a selected surface media to proliferate and ultimately differentiate.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] A drawback of this printing method is the ability of the bioinks such as hydrogels to clog the printing nozzle, due to their high viscosity.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Ideal inkjet bioprinting involves using a low polymer viscosity (ideally below 10 centipoise), low cell density (<10 million cells/mL), and low structural heights (<10 million cells/mL).
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] There are several other bioprinting techniques which are less commonly used.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Droplet-based bioprinting is a technique in which the bioink blend of cells and/or hydrogels are placed in droplets in precise positions.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Most common amongst this approach are thermal and piezoelectric-drop-on-demand techniques.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] This method of bioprinting is often used experimentally with lung and ovarian cancer models.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Thermal technologies use short duration signals to heat the bioink, inducing the formation of small bubbles which are ejected.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Piezoelectric bioprinting has short duration current applied to a piezoelectric actuator, which induces a mechanical vibration capable of ejecting a small globule of bioink through the nozzle.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] A significant aspect of the study of droplet-based approaches to bioprinting is accounting for mechanical and thermal stress cells within the bioink experience near the nozzle-tip as they are extruded.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Bioinks are essential components of the bioprinting process.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] They are composed of living cells and enzymatic supplements to nurture an environment that supports the biological needs of the printed tissue.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The environment created by the bioink allows for the cell to attach, grow, and differentiate into its adult form.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Cell-encapsualting hydrogels are used in extrusion based bioprinting methods, while gelatin MethacryloylGelatin methacrylon (GelMA) and acellular comprised bioinks are most often used in tissue engineering techniques that require cross-linkage and precise structural integrity.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] It is essential for bioinks to help replicate the external cellular matrix environment that the cell would naturally occur in.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting can be used to reconstruct tissue from various regions of the body.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The precursor to the adoption of 3D printing in healthcare was a series of trials conducted by researchers at Boston Children's Hospital.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The team built replacement urinary bladders by hand for seven patients by constructing scaffolds, then layering the scaffolds with cells from the patients and allowing them to grow.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The trials were a success as the patients remained in good health 7 years after implantation, which led a research fellow named Anthony Atala, MD, to search for ways to automate the process.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Patients with end-stage bladder disease can now be treated by using bio-engineered bladder tissues to rebuild the damaged organ.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] This technology can also potentially be applied to bone, skin, cartilage and muscle tissue.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Though one long-term goal of 3D bioprinting technology is to reconstruct an entire organ as well as minimize the problem of the lack of organs for transplantation.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] There has been little success in bioprinting of fully functional organs e.g. liver, skin, meniscus or pancreas.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Unlike implantable stents, organs have complex shapes and are significantly harder to bioprint.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] A bioprinted heart, for example, must not only meet structural requirements, but also vascularization, mechanical load, and electrical signal propagation requirements.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In 2022, the first success of a clinical trial for a 3D bioprinted transplant that is made from the patient's own cells, an external ear to treat microtia, was reported.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The limitations of 3D bioprinting are associated with physiologically irrelevant morphology and unsuccessful histological evaluation methods.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting contributes to significant advances in the medical field of tissue engineering by allowing for research to be done on innovative materials called biomaterials.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Some of the most notable bioengineered substances are usually stronger than the average bodily materials, including soft tissue and bone.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] These constituents can act as future substitutes, even improvements, for the original body materials.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In addition, the Defense Threat Reduction Agency aims to print mini organs such as hearts, livers, and lungs as the potential to test new drugs more accurately and perhaps eliminate the need for testing in animals.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Bioprinting can also be used for cultured meat.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In 2021, a steak-like cultured meat, composed of three types of bovine cell fibers was produced.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The Wagyu-like beef has a structure similar to original meat.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] This technology provides an alternative to natural meat harvesting methods if the livestock industry is plagued by disease.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] In addition, it provides a possible solution to reducing the environmental impact of the livestock industry.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The bioprinting of biofilms uses the same methods as other bioprinting.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Oftentimes, the biofilm begins with an extrusion of a polysaccharide to provide structure for biofilm growth.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] An example of one of these polysaccharides is alginate.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The alginate structure can have microbes embedded within the structure.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Hydrogels can also be used to assist in the formation of functional biofilms.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Biofilms are difficult to analyze in a laboratory setting due to the complex structure and the time it takes for a functional biofilm to form.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting biofilms allows us to skip certain processes and makes it easier to analyze functional biofilms.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Thickness of the biofilm being printed with change the functionality due to nutrient and oxygen diffusion.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Thicker 3D printed biofilms will naturally select for anaerobes for example.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Biofilms are capable of remediation in the natural environment which suggests there is potential in regards to the use of 3D bioprinted biofilm use in environmental remediation.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Microbes are able to degrade a large range of chemicals and metals and providing a structure for these microbes to flourish such as in biofilm structures is beneficial.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Artificial biofilms protect the microbes from the dangers of the environment while promoting signaling and overall microbial interactions.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting allows functional microorganisms to be placed in structures that provide mechanical stability and protects them from environmental conditions.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] The larger contact area provided by 3D printed structures compared to normal environmental structures provides more efficient removal of pollutants.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Bioprinting also has possible uses in the future in assisting in wastewater treatment and in corrosion control.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] When humans come in contact with environmental biofilms, it is possible for infections and long-term health hazards to occur.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Antibiotic penetration and expansion within a biofilm is an area of research which can benefit from bioprinting techniques, to further explore the effect of environmental biofilms on human health.
[src:genetic-engineering/3d-bioprinting] Biofilm printing requires further research due to limited published data and complex protocols.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Economically, *A. tumefaciens* is a serious pathogen of walnuts, grape vines, stone fruits, nut trees, sugar beets, horse radish, and rhubarb, and the persistent nature of the tumors or galls caused by the disease make it particularly harmful for perennial crops.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The classification of *Agrobacterium tumefaciens* and related species, collectively the ***Agrobacterium tumefaciens* species complex**, has greatly outpaced the change in terminology employed by plant scientists.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Before 1980 the division of *Agrobacterium* largely reflected disease symptomology and host range.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] *A. radiobacter* is defined as the "avirulent" species, *A. tumefaciens* the one causing crown gall, *A. rhizogenes* causing hairy root disease, and *A. rubi* causing cane gall.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] With the discovery of the Ti plasmid it was realized that symptomology mostly depend on the particular version of the plasmid carried, not anything that resembles a biological species concept.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] By 2000, the "biovar" concept, using growth and metabolic characteristics, had divided *Agrobacterium* into three biovars later shown to be mostly congruent with genetic differentiation.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Biovar 1 would remain in *Agrobacterium*, biovar 2 to *Rhizobium rhizogenes*, and biovar 3 to *Allorhizobium vitis*.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] By 2014 there is very little, if any, confusion for what *Agrobacterium* in the strict sense would refer to.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] However, another issue remains with the classification inside of biovar 1, specifically inside the *Agrobacterium tumefaciens* species complex, where biological species remain hard to differentiate without DNA sequencing.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Researchers largely still stuck to the old nomenclature based on symptomology, save for a few who take the time to delimit the "genomovars" or "genomospecies" inside of this complex.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] To add to the confusion, the *Approved Lists* of 1980 changed the type strain of *A. tumefaciens* without explanation to "B6", a strain now properly classified as *Agrobacterium radiobacter* (genomovar 4), causing misled researchers to propose the synonymization of the two.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The original type strain of *A. tumefaciens*, reinstated in 2023, belongs to genomovar 1.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Another strain of "A. tumefaciens" commonly used in early research was C58, which belongs to genomovar 8.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] For a review of the currently-known structure of the species complex, see Vargas Ribera et al.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] (2024), which also lists names that have been separately proposed for the genomovars.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This article cites a great number of sources that do not distinguish among the genomovars.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Most text in this article should be treated as describing the species complex as a whole.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] To be virulent, the bacterium contains a tumour-inducing plasmid (Ti plasmid or pTi) 200 kbp long, which contains the T-DNA and all the genes necessary to transfer it to the plant cell.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Many strains of *A. tumefaciens* do not contain a pTi.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Since the Ti plasmid is essential to cause disease, prepenetration events in the rhizosphere occur to promote bacterial conjugation - exchange of plasmids amongst bacteria.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] In the presence of opines, *A. tumefaciens* produces a diffusible conjugation signal called *N*-(3-oxo-octanoyl)-L-homoserine lactone (3OC8HSL) or the *Agrobacterium* autoinducer.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This activates the transcription factor TraR, positively regulating the transcription of genes required for conjugation.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] At least 25 *vir* genes on the Ti plasmid are necessary for tumor induction.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] In addition to their perception role, *virA* and *chvE* induce other *vir* genes.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The VirA protein has autokinase activity: it phosphorylates itself on a histidine residue.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Then the VirA protein phosphorylates the VirG protein on its aspartate residue.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The virG protein is a cytoplasmic protein produced from the *virG* Ti plasmid gene.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] It is a transcription factor, inducing the transcription of the *vir* operons.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The ChvE protein regulates the second mechanism of the *vir* genes' activation.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] It increases VirA protein sensitivity to phenolic compounds.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Following an initial weak and reversible attachment, the bacteria synthesize cellulose fibrils that anchor them to the wounded plant cell to which they were attracted.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Four main genes are involved in this process: *chvA*, *chvB*, *pscA*, and *att*.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The products of the first three genes apparently are involved in the actual synthesis of the cellulose fibrils.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] These fibrils also anchor the bacteria to each other, helping to form a microcolony.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] VirC, the most important virulent protein, is a necessary step in the recombination of illegitimate recolonization.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] It selects the section of the DNA in the host plant that will be replaced and it cuts into this strand of DNA.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] After production of cellulose fibrils, a calcium-dependent outer membrane protein called rhicadhesin is produced, which also aids in sticking the bacteria to the cell wall.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Homologues of this protein can be found in other rhizobia.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Currently, there are several reports on standardisation of protocol for the *Agrobacterium*-mediated transformation.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The effect of different parameters such as infection time, acetosyringone, DTT, and cysteine have been studied in soybean (*Glycine max*).
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] To transfer T-DNA into a plant cell, *A. tumefaciens* uses a type IV secretion mechanism, involving the production of a T-pilus.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] When acetosyringone and other substances are detected, a signal transduction event activates the expression of 11 genes within the VirB operon which are responsible for the formation of the T-pilus.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This is a polypeptide of 121 amino acids which requires processing by the removal of 47 residues to form a T-pilus subunit.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The subunit was thought to be circularized by the formation of a peptide bond between the two ends of the polypeptide.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] However, high-resolution structure of the T-pilus revealed no cyclization of the pilin, with the overall organization of the pilin subunits being highly similar to those of other conjugative pili, such as F-pilus.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Products of the other VirB genes are used to transfer the subunits across the plasma membrane.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Yeast two-hybrid studies provide evidence that VirB6, VirB7, VirB8, VirB9 and VirB10 may all encode components of the transporter.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] An ATPase for the active transport of the subunits would also be required.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The T-DNA must be cut out of the circular plasmid.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This is typically done by the Vir genes within the helper plasmid.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] A VirD1/D2 complex nicks the DNA at the left and right border sequences.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The VirD2 protein is covalently attached to the 5' end.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] VirD2 contains a motif that leads to the nucleoprotein complex being targeted to the type IV secretion system (T4SS).
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The structure of the T-pilus showed that the central channel of the pilus is too narrow to allow the transfer of the folded VirD2, suggesting that VirD2 must be partially unfolded during the conjugation process.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] In the cytoplasm of the recipient cell, the T-DNA complex becomes coated with VirE2 proteins, which are exported through the T4SS independently from the T-DNA complex.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Nuclear localization signals, or NLSs, located on the VirE2 and VirD2, are recognised by the importin alpha protein, which then associates with importin beta and the nuclear pore complex to transfer the T-DNA into the nucleus.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] VIP1 also appears to be an important protein in the process, possibly acting as an adapter to bring the VirE2 to the importin.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Once inside the nucleus, VIP2 may target the T-DNA to areas of chromatin that are being actively transcribed, so that the T-DNA can integrate into the host genome.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] To cause gall formation, the T-DNA encodes genes for the production of auxin or indole-3-acetic acid via the IAM pathway.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This biosynthetic pathway is not used in many plants for the production of auxin, so it means the plant has no molecular means of regulating it and auxin will be produced constitutively.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Genes for the production of cytokinins are also expressed.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This stimulates cell proliferation and gall formation.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The T-DNA contains genes for encoding enzymes that cause the plant to create specialized amino acid derivatives which the bacteria can metabolize, called opines.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Opines are a class of chemicals that serve as a source of nitrogen for *A. tumefaciens*, but not for most other organisms.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The specific type of opine produced by *A. tumefaciens* C58 infected plants is nopaline.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Two nopaline type Ti plasmids, pTi-SAKURA and pTiC58, were fully sequenced.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] "*A. fabrum*" C58, the first fully sequenced pathovar, was first isolated from a cherry tree crown gall.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The genome was simultaneously sequenced by Goodner *et al.* and Wood *et al.* in 2001.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The genome of strain C58consists of a circular chromosome, two plasmids, and a linear chromosome.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The presence of a covalently bonded circular chromosome is common to Bacteria, with few exceptions.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] However, the presence of both a single circular chromosome and single linear chromosome is unique to a group in this genus.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The two plasmids are pTiC58, responsible for the processes involved in virulence, and pAtC58, once dubbed the "cryptic" plasmid.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The pAtC58 plasmid has been shown to be involved in the metabolism of opines and to conjugate with other bacteria in the absence of the pTiC58 plasmid.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] If the Ti plasmid is removed, the tumor growth that is the means of classifying this species of bacteria does not occur.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The Asilomar Conference in 1975 established widespread agreement that recombinant techniques were insufficiently understood and needed to be tightly controlled.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The DNA transmission capabilities of *Agrobacterium* have been vastly explored in biotechnology as a means of inserting foreign genes into plants.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Shortly after the Asilomar Conference, Marc Van Montagu and Jeff Schell discovered the gene transfer mechanism between *Agrobacterium* and plants, which resulted in the development of methods to alter the bacterium into an efficient delivery system for genetic engineering in plants.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The plasmid T-DNA that is transferred to the plant is an ideal vehicle for genetic engineering.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This is done by cloning a desired gene sequence into T-DNA binary vectors that will be used to deliver a sequence of interest into eukaryotic cells.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This process has been performed using the firefly luciferase gene to produce glowing plants.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This luminescence has been a useful device in the study of plant chloroplast function and as a reporter gene.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] It is also possible to transform *Arabidopsis thaliana* by dipping flowers into a broth of *Agrobacterium*: the seed produced will be transgenic.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Under laboratory conditions, T-DNA has also been transferred to human cells, demonstrating the diversity of insertion application.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The mechanism by which *Agrobacterium* inserts materials into the host cell is by a type IV secretion system which is very similar to mechanisms used by pathogens to insert materials (usually proteins) into human cells by type III secretion.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] It also employs a type of signaling conserved in many Gram-negative bacteria called quorum sensing.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This makes *Agrobacterium* an important topic of medical research, as well.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Natural genetic transformation in bacteria is a sexual process involving the transfer of DNA from one cell to another through the intervening medium, and the integration of the donor sequence into the recipient genome by homologous recombination.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] *A. tumefaciens* can undergo natural transformation in soil without any specific physical or chemical treatment.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Crown gall disease caused by *Agrobacterium tumefaciens* can be controlled by using various methods.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The best way to control this disease is to take preventative measures, such as sterilizing pruning tools so as to avoid infecting new plants.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Performing mandatory inspections of nursery stock and rejecting infected plants as well as not planting susceptible plants in infected fields are also valuable practices.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Avoiding wounding the crowns/roots of the plants during cultivation is important for preventing disease.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] In horticultural techniques in which multiple plants are joined to grow as one, such as budding and grafting these techniques lead to plant wounds.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Wounds are the primary location of bacterial entry into the host plant.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Therefore, it is advisable to perform these techniques during times of the year when *Agrobacteria* are not active.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Control of root-chewing insects is also helpful to reduce levels of infection, since these insects cause wounds (a.k.a. bacterial entryways) in the plant roots.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] It is recommended that infected plant material be burned rather than placed in a compost pile due to the bacteria's ability to live in the soil for many years.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Biological control methods are also utilized in managing this disease.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] During the 1970s and 1980s, a common practice for treating germinated seeds, seedlings, and rootstock was to soak them in a suspension of K84.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] K84 is a strain of *Rhizobium rhizogenes* (formerly classified under *A. radiobacter*, but later reclassified) which is a species related to *A. tumefaciens* but is not pathogenic.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] K84 produces a bacteriocin (agrocin 84) which is an antibiotic specific against related bacteria, including *A. tumefaciens*.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This method, which was successful at controlling the disease on a commercial scale, had the risk of K84 transferring its resistance gene to the pathogenic *Agrobacteria*.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Thus, in the 1990s, a deletion mutant strain based on K84, known as K1026, was created.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] This strain is just as successful in controlling crown gall as K84 without the caveat of resistance gene transfer.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Host, environment, and pathogen are extremely important concepts in regards to plant pathology.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] *Agrobacteria* have the widest host range of any plant pathogen, so the main factor to take into consideration in the case of crown gall is environment.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] There are various conditions and factors that make for a conducive environment for *A. tumefaciens* when infecting its various hosts.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The bacterium can't penetrate the host plant without an entry point such as a wound.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Factors leading to wounds in plants include cultural practices, grafting, freezing injury, growth cracks, soil insects, and other animals in the environment causing damage to the plant.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Consequently, in exceptionally harsh winters, it is common to have an increased incidence of crown gall due to the weather-related damage.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Along with this, there are methods of mediating infection of the host plant.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] For example, nematodes can act as a vector to introduce *Agrobacterium* into plant roots.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] More specifically, the root parasitic nematodes damage the plant cell, creating a wound for the bacteria to enter through.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Finally, temperature is a factor when considering *A. tumefaciens* infection.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] The optimal temperature for crown gall formation due to this bacterium is 22 °C (72 °F) because of the thermosensitivity of T-DNA transfer.
[src:genetic-engineering/a-tumefaciens] Tumor formation is significantly reduced at higher temperature conditions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is essentially unavoidable.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress affects animals, but plants are especially dependent, if not solely dependent, on environmental factors, so it is particularly constraining.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is the most harmful factor concerning the growth and productivity of crops worldwide.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Research has also shown that abiotic stressors are at their most harmful when they occur together, in combinations of abiotic stress factors.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] The most common of the stressors are the easiest for people to identify, but there are many other, less recognizable abiotic stress factors which affect environments constantly.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Lesser-known stressors generally occur on a smaller scale.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] They include: poor edaphic conditions like rock content and pH levels, high radiation, compaction, contamination, and other, highly specific conditions like rapid rehydration during seed germination.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress, as a natural part of every ecosystem, will affect organisms in a variety of ways.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Although these effects may be either beneficial or detrimental, the location of the area is crucial in determining the extent of the impact that abiotic stress will have.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] The higher the latitude of the area affected, the greater the impact of abiotic stress will be on that area.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] So, a taiga or boreal forest is at the mercy of whatever abiotic stress factors may come along, while tropical zones are much less susceptible to such stressors.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] While abiotic stress may have negative impacts on individual organisms, there are cases where abiotic stress plays an important role in maintaining a healthy ecosystem.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Important ecosystem mechanisms and improved overall stress tolerance may rely on occasional low levels of abiotic stress.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] One example of a situation where abiotic stress plays a constructive role in an ecosystem is in natural wildfires.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Smaller fires are useful in reducing the overall fuel load of an area of forest or prairie.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] By clearing out dead brush and other organic matter, the risk of catastrophic and widespread fire decreases, and the residual ash of smaller fires helps add nutrients back into the soil.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] The observed benefits of these smaller and more controlled fires on land usability and species populations have led to the use of prescribed burning by humans for centuries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Varying perspectives on the benefits and risks of fire to ecosystems have influenced official policy through history.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Forest Service, initially focused on fire control, changed its policy to one of fire management in 1974, recognizing these fires as a natural part of an ecosystem.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] There is also evidence that a diverse fire history between patches of land within an area has been shown to benefit transitional landscapes between savanna and forest.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Even though it is healthy for an ecosystem, a wildfire can still be considered an abiotic stressor, because it puts stress on individual organisms within the area.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] On the larger scale, though, natural wildfires are positive manifestations of abiotic stress.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] What also needs to be taken into account when looking for benefits of abiotic stress, is that one phenomenon may not affect an entire ecosystem in the same way.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] While a flood will kill most plants living low on the ground in a certain area, if there is rice there, it will thrive in the wet conditions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Another example of this is in phytoplankton and zooplankton.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] The same types of conditions are usually considered stressful for these two types of organisms.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] They act very similarly when exposed to ultraviolet light and most toxins, but at elevated temperatures the phytoplankton reacts negatively, while the thermophilic zooplankton reacts positively to the increase in temperature.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] The two may be living in the same environment, but an increase in temperature of the area would prove stressful only for one of the organisms.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Lastly, abiotic stress has enabled species to grow, develop, and evolve, through the process of natural selection.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Heritable traits that improve an organism's resiliency under stressed conditions increase the likelihood that the organism will survive and reproduce, enabling it to pass these traits to the next generation.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Both plants and animals have evolved mechanisms allowing them to survive extremes.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] One of the detriments concerning abiotic stress involves farming.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] It has been claimed by one study that abiotic stress causes the most crop loss of any other factor and that most major crops are reduced in their yield by more than 50% from their potential yield.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Because abiotic stress is widely considered a detrimental effect, the research on this branch of the issue is extensive.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] For more information on the harmful effects of abiotic stress, see the sections below on plants and animals.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] A plant's first line of defense against abiotic stress is in its roots.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] If the soil holding the plant is healthy and biologically diverse, the plant will have a higher chance of surviving stressful conditions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] The plant responses to stress are dependent on the tissue or organ affected by the stress.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] For example, transcriptional responses to stress are tissue or cell specific in roots and are quite different depending on the stress involved.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] One of the primary responses to abiotic stress such as high salinity is the disruption of the Na+/K+ ratio in the cytoplasm of the plant cell.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] High concentrations of Na+, for example, can decrease the capacity for the plant to take up water and also alter enzyme and transporter functions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Evolved adaptations to efficiently restore cellular ion homeostasis have led to a wide variety of stress tolerant plants.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Facilitation, or the positive interactions between different species of plants, is an intricate web of association in a natural environment.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] In areas of high stress, the level of facilitation is especially high as well.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] This could possibly be because the plants need a stronger network to survive in a harsher environment, so their interactions between species, such as cross-pollination or mutualistic actions, become more common to cope with the severity of their habitat.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Plants also adapt very differently from one another, even from a plant living in the same area.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] When a group of different plant species was prompted by a variety of different stress signals, such as drought or cold, each plant responded uniquely.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Hardly any of the responses were similar, even though the plants had become accustomed to exactly the same home environment.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Serpentine soils (media with low concentrations of nutrients and high concentrations of heavy metals) can be a source of abiotic stress.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Initially, the absorption of toxic metal ions is limited by cell membrane exclusion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Ions that are absorbed into tissues are sequestered in cell vacuoles.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] This sequestration mechanism is facilitated by proteins on the vacuole membrane.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] An example of plants that adapt to serpentine soil are Metallophytes, or hyperaccumulators, as they are known for their ability to absorbed heavy metals using the root-to-shoot translocation (which it will absorb into shoots rather than the plant itself).
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] They're also extinguished for their ability to absorb toxic substances from heavy metals.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Chemical priming has been proposed to increase tolerance to abiotic stresses in crop plants.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] In this method, which is analogous to vaccination, stress-inducing chemical agents are introduced to the plant in brief doses so that the plant begins preparing defense mechanisms.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Thus, when the abiotic stress occurs, the plant has already prepared defense mechanisms that can be activated faster and increase tolerance.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress mostly affects plants used in agriculture.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Some examples of adverse conditions (which may be caused by climate change) are high or low temperatures, drought, salinity, and toxins.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Elevated global temperatures present a severe bottleneck for crop yields, as heat stress alters membrane fluidity, accelerates destructive transpiration rates, and heavily impairs a plant's overall Water Use Efficiency (WUE).
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] When crops encounter extreme thermal environments during early reproductive or vegetative stages, cellular homeostasis is broken down, causing grain yield reduction and premature leaf senescence.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] To mitigate down-stream damage from overlapping thermal and drought shocks, advanced ex-ante strategies such as physical seed priming or chemical priming agents are applied.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] These priming interventions activate early molecular, enzymatic, and hormonal pre-defense responses within the seed tissue, enabling the plant to maintain higher functional stability and lower oxidative injury when heat stress occurs later in the field environment.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Flooding acts as a compound environmental stressor that is broadly categorized into waterlogging (where only the root system is inundated) and complete submergence (where the entire plant is covered by water).
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] The primary hazard of flooding is gas diffusion restriction, which triggers oxygen starvation (hypoxia or anoxia) in the rhizosphere and alters essential plant hormone signaling networks, such as the regulation between Sub1A and non-Sub1A genotypes in rice.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] To cope with complete submergence, tolerant plants rely on distinct physiological survival strategies.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Furthermore, monitoring maximum quantum yield performance reveals that preserving photosynthetic efficiency during transient flooding stress is paramount to driving rapid physiological recovery once the water recedes.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Soil acidity acts as a sweeping abiotic stress factor on global arable lands, primarily because low pH environments trigger dangerous chemical toxicities dominated by soluble aluminum (Al3+ )and iron, which structurally damage root anatomy and limit basic development.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] High acidity also locks up vital macronutrients, causing severe phosphorus starvation stress that forces plants to aggressively modify their lateral root structures to maximize surface area absorption.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] To remediate heavy-metal-polluted and highly acidic substrates, bioremediation utilizes hyperaccumulator plant traits (metallophytes).
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] These specialized plants successfully survive the toxicity of acidic media by relying on a highly developed root-to-shoot translocation system, which efficiently absorbs and transports toxic ions away from fragile root tissues and sequesters them safely inside the upper shoot vacuoles.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Soil salinization, the accumulation of water-soluble salts to levels that negatively impact plant production, is a global phenomenon affecting approximately 831 million hectares of land.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] More specifically, the phenomenon threatens 19.5% of the world's irrigated agricultural land and 2.1% of the world's non-irrigated (dry-land) agricultural lands.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] High soil salinity content can be harmful to plants because water-soluble salts can alter osmotic potential gradients and consequently inhibit many cellular functions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Over generations, many plants have mutated and built different mechanisms to counter salinity effects.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] A good combatant of salinity in plants is the hormone ethylene.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Ethylene is known for regulating plant growth and development and dealing with stress conditions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Many central membrane proteins in plants, such as ETO2, ERS1 and EIN2, are used for ethylene signaling in many plant growth processes.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Mutations in these proteins can lead to heightened salt sensitivity and can limit plant growth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] The effects of salinity has been studied on *Arabidopsis* plants that have mutated ERS1, ERS2, ETR1, ETR2 and EIN4 proteins.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] These proteins are used for ethylene signaling against certain stress conditions, such as salt and the ethylene precursor ACC is used to suppress any sensitivity to the salt stress.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus (P) is an essential macronutrient required for plant growth and development, but it is present only in limited quantities in most of the world's soil.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Plants use P mainly in the form of soluble inorganic phosphates (PO4−−−) but are subject to abiotic stress when there is not enough soluble PO4−−− in the soil.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus forms insoluble complexes with Ca and Mg in alkaline soils and with Al and Fe in acidic soils that make the phosphorus unavailable for plant roots.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] It has been shown that PHR1, a MYB-related transcription factor, is a master regulator of P-starvation response in plants.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Drought stress, defined as naturally occurring water deficit, is a main cause of crop losses in agriculture.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] This is because water is essential for many fundamental processes in plant growth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] It has become especially important in recent years to find a way to combat drought stress.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] A decrease in precipitation and consequent increase in drought are extremely likely in the future due to an increase in global warming.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Plants have come up with many mechanisms and adaptations to try and deal with drought stress.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] One of the leading ways that plants combat drought stress is by closing their stomata.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] A key hormone regulating stomatal opening and closing is abscisic acid (ABA).
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Synthesis of ABA causes the ABA to bind to receptors.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] This binding then affects the opening of ion channels, thereby decreasing turgor pressure in the stomata and causing them to close.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Recent studies by Gonzalez-Villagra, et al., have shown how ABA levels increased in drought-stressed plants (2018).
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] They showed that when plants were placed in a stressful situation, they produced more ABA to try to conserve any water they had in their leaves.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Another extremely important factor in dealing with drought stress and regulating the uptake and export of water is aquaporins (AQPs).
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] AQPs are integral membrane proteins that make up channels.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] These channels' main job is the transport of water and other essential solutes.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] AQPs are both transcriptionally and post-transcriptionally regulated by many different factors such as ABA, GA3, pH and Ca2+; and the specific levels of AQPs in certain parts of the plant, such as roots or leaves, helps to draw as much water into the plant as possible.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] By understanding the mechanisms of both AQPs and the hormone ABA, scientists will be better able to produce drought-resistant plants in the future.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] A study by Tombesi et al., found that plants which had previously been exposed to drought were able to minimize water loss and decrease water use.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] They found that plants which were exposed to drought conditions actually changed the way they regulated their stomata and what they called "hydraulic safety margin" so as to decrease the vulnerability of the plant.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] By changing the regulation of stomata and subsequently the transpiration, plants were able to function better when less water was available.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] For animals, the most stressful of all the abiotic stressors is heat.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] This is because many species are unable to regulate their internal body temperature.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Even in the species that are able to regulate their own temperature, it is not always a completely accurate system.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Temperature determines metabolic rates, heart rates, and other very important factors within the bodies of animals, so an extreme temperature change can easily distress the animal's body.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Animals can respond to extreme heat, for example, through natural heat acclimation or by burrowing into the ground to find a cooler space.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] It is also possible to see in animals that a high genetic diversity is beneficial in providing resiliency against harsh abiotic stressors.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] This acts as a sort of stock room when a species is plagued by the perils of natural selection.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] A variety of galling insects are among the most specialized and diverse herbivores on the planet, and their extensive protections against abiotic stress factors have helped the insect in gaining that position of honor.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Biodiversity is determined by many things, and one of them is abiotic stress.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] If an environment is highly stressful, biodiversity tends to be low.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] If abiotic stress does not have a strong presence in an area, the biodiversity will be much higher.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] This idea leads into the understanding of how abiotic stress and endangered species are related.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] It has been observed through a variety of environments that as the level of abiotic stress increases, the number of species decreases.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] This means that species are more likely to become population threatened, endangered, and even extinct, when and where abiotic stress is especially harsh.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Data suggests that anthropogenic activity has increased the global temperature, and likely increased the odds of extreme climate events such as drought, fire conditions and flooding.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] Threats to organisms and ecosystem biodiversity due to increased abiotic stress are one major impact of this change.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] The effects of climate change on biomes vary due to the location, patterns of precipitation, and the organisms which inhabit them.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] On the species level, the increased abiotic stress due to climate change can lead to adaptations which increase a species' reproductive success under these conditions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abiotic-stress] However, such highly specialized adaptations may leave species vulnerable to other stresses.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Public health researchers and organizations have also framed access to legal abortion as a public health measure, given its association with reduced maternal mortality.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the United States.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] China, which has ended its one-child policy and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of its population control strategy.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:genetic-engineering/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] In 1938, Buckminster Fuller introduced the word ephemeralization to describe the trends of "doing more with less" in chemistry, health and other areas of industrial development.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] In 1946, Fuller published a chart of the discoveries of the chemical elements over time to highlight the development of accelerating acceleration in human knowledge acquisition.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Toynbee it was "not an article of faith" but "a datum of observation and experience history" that history was accelerating, and "at an accelerating rate".
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] In a series of published articles from 1974 to 1979, and then in his 1988 book *Mind Children*, computer scientist and futurist Hans Moravec generalized Moore's law to make predictions about the future of artificial life.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Moore's law describes an exponential growth pattern in the complexity of integrated semiconductor circuits.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Moravec extended this to include technologies from long before the integrated circuit to future forms of technology.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Moravec outlined a timeline and a scenario in which robots could evolve into a new series of artificial species, starting around 2030–2040.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] In his TV series *Connections* (1978)—and sequels *Connections2* (1994) and *Connections3* (1997)—James Burke explores an "Alternative View of Change" (the subtitle of the series) that rejects the conventional linear and teleological view of historical progress.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Burke contends that one cannot consider the development of any particular piece of the modern world in isolation.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] The interplay of the results of these isolated events is what drives history and innovation, and is also the main focus of the series and its sequels.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Burke also explores three corollaries to his initial thesis.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] The first is that, if history is driven by individuals who act only on what they know at the time, and not because of any idea as to where their actions will eventually lead, then predicting the future course of technological progress is merely conjecture.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Therefore, if we are astonished by the connections Burke is able to weave among past events, then we will be equally surprised to what the events of today eventually will lead, especially events we were not even aware of at the time.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] The second and third corollaries are explored most in the introductory and concluding episodes, and they represent the downside of an interconnected history.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] If history progresses because of the synergistic interaction of past events and innovations, then as history does progress, the number of these events and innovations increases.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] This increase in possible connections causes the process of innovation to not only continue, but to accelerate.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Burke poses the question of what happens when this rate of innovation, or more importantly change itself, becomes too much for the average person to handle, and what this means for individual power, liberty, and privacy.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] In his book *Mindsteps to the Cosmos* (HarperCollins, August 1983), Gerald S.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Hawkins elucidated his notion of *mindsteps*, dramatic and irreversible changes to paradigms or world views.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] He identified five distinct mindsteps in human history, and the technology that accompanied these "new world views": the invention of imagery, writing, mathematics, printing, the telescope, rocket, radio, TV, computer...
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] "Each one takes the collective mind closer to reality, one stage further along in its understanding of the relation of humans to the cosmos." He noted: "The waiting period between the mindsteps is getting shorter.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] One can't help noticing the acceleration." Hawkins' empirical 'mindstep equation' quantified this, and gave dates for future mindsteps.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] The date of the next mindstep (5; the series begins at 0) is given as 2021, with two further, successively closer mindsteps in 2045 and 2051, until the limit of the series in 2053.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] His subsequent Hugo award-winning novel *A Fire Upon the Deep* (1992) starts with an imaginative description of the evolution of a superintelligence passing through exponentially accelerating developmental stages ending in a transcendent, almost omnipotent power unfathomable by mere humans.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] His already mentioned influential 1993 paper on the technological singularity compactly summarizes the basic ideas.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] In his 1999 book *The Age of Spiritual Machines*, Ray Kurzweil proposed *The Law of Accelerating Returns*, according to which the rate of change in a wide variety of evolutionary systems (including but not limited to the growth of technologies) tends to increase exponentially.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] He gave further focus to this issue in a 2001 essay entitled "The Law of Accelerating Returns".
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] In it, Kurzweil, after Moravec, argued for extending Moore's Law to describe exponential growth of diverse forms of technological progress.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Whenever a technology approaches some kind of a barrier, according to Kurzweil, a new technology will be invented to allow us to cross that barrier.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] He cites numerous past examples of this to substantiate his assertions.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] He predicts that such paradigm shifts have and will continue to become increasingly common, leading to "technological change so rapid and profound it represents a rupture in the fabric of human history".
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] He believes *The Law of Accelerating Returns* implies that a technological singularity will occur before the end of the 21st century, around 2045.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Already within the past sixty years, life in the industrialized world has changed almost beyond recognition except for living memories from the first half of the 20th century.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] This pattern will culminate in unimaginable technological progress in the 21st century, leading to a singularity.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Kurzweil elaborates on his views in his books *The Age of Spiritual Machines* and *The Singularity Is Near*.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] In the natural sciences, it is typical that processes characterized by exponential acceleration in their initial stages go into the saturation phase.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] This clearly makes it possible to realize that if an increase with acceleration is observed over a certain period of time, this does not mean an endless continuation of this process.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] On the contrary, in many cases this means an early exit to the plateau of speed.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] The processes occurring in natural science allow us to suggest that the observed picture of accelerating scientific and technological progress, after some time (in physical processes, as a rule, is short) will be replaced by a slowdown and a complete stop.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Accelerating change may not be restricted to the Anthropocene Epoch, but a general and predictable developmental feature of the universe.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] The physical processes that generate an acceleration such as Moore's law are positive feedback loops giving rise to exponential or superexponential technological change.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] These dynamics lead to increasingly efficient and dense configurations of Space, Time, Energy, and Matter (STEM efficiency and density, or STEM "compression").
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] At the physical limit, this developmental process of accelerating change leads to black hole density organizations, a conclusion also reached by studies of the ultimate physical limits of computation in the universe.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Applying this vision to the search for extraterrestrial intelligence leads to the idea that advanced intelligent life reconfigures itself into a black hole.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Such advanced life forms would be interested in inner space, rather than outer space and interstellar expansion.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] They would thus in some way transcend reality, not be observable and it would be a solution to Fermi's paradox called the "transcension hypothesis".
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Another solution is that the black holes we observe could actually be interpreted as intelligent super-civilizations feeding on stars, or "stellivores".
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] This dynamics of evolution and development is an invitation to study the universe itself as evolving, developing.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] If the universe is a kind of superorganism, it may possibly tend to reproduce, naturally or artificially, with intelligent life playing a role.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Dramatic changes in the rate of economic growth have occurred in the past because of some technological advancement.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Based on population growth, the economy doubled every 250,000 years from the Paleolithic era until the Neolithic Revolution.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] The new agricultural economy doubled every 900 years, a remarkable increase.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] In the current era, beginning with the Industrial Revolution, the world's economic output doubles every fifteen years, sixty times faster than during the agricultural era.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] If the rise of superhuman intelligence causes a similar revolution, argues Robin Hanson, then one would expect the economy to double at least quarterly and possibly on a weekly basis.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] In his 1981 book *Critical Path*, futurist and inventor R.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Buckminster Fuller estimated that if we took all the knowledge that mankind had accumulated and transmitted by the year One CE as equal to one unit of information, it probably took about 1500 years (or until the sixteenth century) for that amount of knowledge to double.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] The next doubling of knowledge from two to four "knowledge units" took only 250 years, until about 1750 CE.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] By 1900, one hundred and fifty years later, knowledge had doubled again to 8 units.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] The observed speed at which information doubled was getting faster and faster.
[src:genetic-engineering/accelerating-change] Both Theodore Modis and Jonathan Huebner have argued—each from different perspectives—that by the late-2010s, the rate of technological innovation had not only ceased to rise, but was actually then declining.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] One goal of acoustical engineering can be the reduction of unwanted noise, which is referred to as noise control.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Unwanted noise can have significant impacts on animal and human health and well-being, reduce attainment by students in schools, and cause hearing loss.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Noise control principles are implemented into technology and design in a variety of ways, including control by redesigning sound sources, the design of noise barriers, sound absorbers, suppressors, and buffer zones, and the use of hearing protection (earmuffs or earplugs).
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Acoustic engineers usually possess a bachelor's degree or higher qualification in acoustics, physics or another engineering discipline.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Practicing as an acoustic engineer usually requires a bachelor's degree with significant scientific and mathematical content.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Acoustic engineers might work in acoustic consultancy, specializing in particular fields, such as architectural acoustics, environmental noise or vibration control.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] In other industries, acoustic engineers might: design automobile sound systems; investigate human response to sounds, such as urban soundscapes and domestic appliances; develop audio signal processing software for mixing desks, and design loudspeakers and microphones for mobile phones.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Acousticians are also involved in researching and understanding sound scientifically.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Some positions, such as faculty require a Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] In most countries, a degree in acoustics can represent the first step towards professional certification and the degree program may be certified by a professional body.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] After completing a certified degree program the engineer must satisfy a range of requirements before being certified.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Once certified, the engineer is designated the title of Chartered Engineer (in most Commonwealth countries).
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] The listed subdisciplines are loosely based on the PACS (Physics and Astronomy Classification Scheme) coding used by the Acoustical Society of America.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Aeroacoustics is concerned with how noise is generated by the movement of air, for instance via turbulence, and how sound propagates through the fluid air.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Aeroacoustics plays an important role in understanding how noise is generated by aircraft and wind turbines, as well as exploring how wind instruments work.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Audio signal processing is the electronic manipulation of audio signals using analog and digital signal processing.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Audio engineers develop and use audio signal processing algorithms.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Architectural acoustics (also known as **building acoustics**) is the science and engineering of achieving a good sound within a building.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Architectural acoustics can be about achieving good speech intelligibility in a theatre, restaurant or railway station, enhancing the quality of music in a concert hall or recording studio, or suppressing noise to make offices and homes more productive and pleasant places to work and live.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Architectural acoustic design is usually done by acoustic consultants.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Bioacoustics concerns the scientific study of sound production and hearing in animals.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] It can include: acoustic communication and associated animal behavior and evolution of species; how sound is produced by animals; the auditory mechanisms and neurophysiology of animals; the use of sound to monitor animal populations, and the effect of man-made noise on animals.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] This branch of acoustic engineering deals with the design of headphones, microphones, loudspeakers, sound systems, sound reproduction, and recording.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] There has been a rapid increase in the use of portable electronic devices which can reproduce sound and rely on electroacoustic engineering, e.g. mobile phones, portable media players, and tablet computers.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] The term "electroacoustics" is also used to describe a set of electrokinetic effects that occur in heterogeneous liquids under influence of ultrasound.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Environmental acoustics is concerned with the control of noise and vibrations caused by traffic, aircraft, industrial equipment, recreational activities and anything else that might be considered a nuisance.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Acoustical engineers concerned with environmental acoustics face the challenge of measuring or predicting likely noise levels, determining an acceptable level for that noise, and determining how the noise can be controlled.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Environmental acoustics work is usually done by acoustic consultants or those working in environmental health.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Recent research work has put a strong emphasis on soundscapes, the positive use of sound (e.g. fountains, bird song), and the preservation of tranquility.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Musical acoustics is concerned with researching and describing the physics of music and its perception – how sounds employed as music work.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] This includes: the function and design of musical instruments including electronic synthesizers; the human voice (the physics and neurophysiology of singing); computer analysis of music and composition; the clinical use of music in music therapy, and the perception and cognition of music.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Noise control is a set of strategies to reduce noise pollution by reducing noise at its source, by inhibiting sound propagation using noise barriers or similar, or by the use of ear protection (earmuffs or earplugs).
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Control at the source is the most cost-effective way of providing noise control.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Noise control engineering applied to cars and trucks is known as noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH).
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Other techniques to reduce product noise include vibration isolation, application of acoustic absorbent and acoustic enclosures.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Acoustical engineering can go beyond noise control to look at what is the best sound for a product, for instance, manipulating the sound of door closures on automobiles.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Psychoacoustics tries to explain how humans respond to what they hear, whether that is an annoying noise or beautiful music.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] In many branches of acoustic engineering, a human listener is a final arbitrator as to whether a design is successful, for instance, whether sound localisation works in a surround sound system.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Speech is a major area of study for acoustical engineering, including the production, processing and perception of speech.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] This can include physics, physiology, psychology, audio signal processing and linguistics.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Speech recognition and speech synthesis are two important aspects of the machine processing of speech.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Ensuring speech is transmitted intelligibly, efficiently and with high quality; in rooms, through public address systems and through telephone systems are other important areas of study.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Ultrasonics deals with sound waves in solids, liquids and gases at frequencies too high to be heard by the average person.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Specialist areas include medical ultrasonics (including medical ultrasonography), sonochemistry, nondestructive testing, material characterisation and underwater acoustics (sonar).
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Underwater acoustics is the scientific study of sound in water.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] It is concerned with both natural and man-made sound and its generation underwater; how it propagates, and the perception of the sound by animals.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Applications include sonar to locate submerged objects such as submarines, underwater communication by animals, observation of sea temperatures for climate change monitoring, and marine biology.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Acoustic engineers working on vibration study the motions and interactions of mechanical systems with their environments, including measurement, analysis and control.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Although the way in which sound interacts with its surroundings is often extremely complex, there are a few ideal sound wave behaviours that are fundamental to understanding acoustical design.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Complex sound wave behaviors include absorption, reverberation, diffraction, and refraction.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Absorption is the loss of energy that occurs when a sound wave reflects off of a surface, and refers to both the sound energy transmitted through and dissipated by the surface material.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Reverberation is the persistence of sound caused by repeated boundary reflections after the source of the sound stops.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] This principle is particularly important in enclosed spaces.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Diffraction is the bending of sound waves around surfaces in the path of the wave.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Refraction is the bending of sound waves caused by changes in the medium through which the wave is passing.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] For example, temperature gradients can cause sound wave refraction.
[src:genetic-engineering/acoustical-engineering] Acoustical engineers apply these fundamental concepts, along with mathematical analysis, to control sound for a variety of applications.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] "Aeronautical engineering" was the original term for the field.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] As flight technology advanced to include vehicles operating in outer space, the broader term "aerospace engineering" has come into use.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Aerospace engineering, particularly the astronautics branch, is often colloquially referred to as "rocket science".
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Flight vehicles are subjected to demanding conditions such as those caused by changes in atmospheric pressure and temperature, with structural loads applied upon vehicle components.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Consequently, they are usually the products of various technological and engineering disciplines including aerodynamics, air propulsion, avionics, materials science, structural analysis and manufacturing.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The interaction between these technologies is known as aerospace engineering.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Because of the complexity and number of disciplines involved, aerospace engineering is carried out by teams of engineers, each having their own specialized area of expertise.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The origin of aerospace engineering can be traced back to the aviation pioneers around the late 19th to early 20th centuries, although the work of Sir George Cayley dates from the last decade of the 18th to the mid-19th century.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] One of the most important people in the history of aeronautics and a pioneer in aeronautical engineering, Cayley is credited as the first person to separate the forces of lift and drag, which affect any atmospheric flight vehicle.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Early knowledge of aeronautical engineering was largely empirical, with some concepts and skills imported from other branches of engineering.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Some key elements, like fluid dynamics, were understood by 18th-century scientists.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] In December 1903, the Wright Brothers performed the first sustained, controlled flight of a powered, heavier-than-air aircraft, lasting 12 seconds.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The 1910s saw the development of aeronautical engineering through the design of World War I military aircraft.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] In 1914, Robert Goddard was granted two U.S. patents for rockets using solid fuel, liquid fuel, multiple propellant charges, and multi-stage designs.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] This would set the stage for future applications in multi-stage propulsion systems for outer space.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Congress established the first aeronautical research administration, known as the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, or NACA.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] It was the first government-sponsored organization to support aviation research.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Though intended as an advisory board upon inception, the Langley Aeronautical Laboratory became its first sponsored research and testing facility in 1920.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The organization would later be redefined as NASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Between World Wars I and II, great leaps were made in the field, accelerated by the advent of mainstream civil aviation.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Notable airplanes of this era include the Curtiss JN 4, Farman F.60 Goliath, and Fokker Trimotor.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Notable military airplanes of this period include the Mitsubishi A6M Zero, Supermarine Spitfire and Messerschmitt Bf 109 from Japan, United Kingdom, and Germany respectively.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] A significant development came with the first operational Jet engine-powered airplane, the Messerschmitt Me 262 which entered service in 1944 towards the end of the Second World War.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The first definition of aerospace engineering appeared in February 1958, considering the Earth's atmosphere and outer space as a single realm, thereby encompassing both aircraft (*aero*) and spacecraft (*space*) under the newly coined term *aerospace*.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] In response to the USSR launching the first satellite, Sputnik, into space on October 4, 1957, U.S. aerospace engineers launched the first American satellite on January 31, 1958.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The National Aeronautics and Space Administration was founded in 1958 after the Sputnik crisis.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] In 1969, Apollo 11, the first human space mission to land on the Moon, took place.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] It saw three astronauts enter orbit around the Moon, with two, Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin, visiting the lunar surface.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The third astronaut, Michael Collins, stayed in orbit to rendezvous with Armstrong and Aldrin after their visit.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] An important innovation came on January 30, 1970, when the Boeing 747 made its first commercial flight from New York to London.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] This aircraft made history and became known as the "Jumbo Jet" or "Queen of the Skies" due to its ability to hold up to 480 passengers.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Another significant development came in 1976, with the development of the first passenger supersonic aircraft, the Concorde.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The development of this aircraft was agreed upon by the French and British on November 29, 1962.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] On December 21, 1988, the Antonov An-225 *Mriya* cargo aircraft commenced its first flight.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] It holds the records for the world's heaviest aircraft, heaviest airlifted cargo, and longest airlifted cargo of any aircraft in operational service.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] On October 25, 2007, the Airbus A380 made its maiden commercial flight from Singapore to Sydney, Australia.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] This aircraft was the first passenger plane to surpass the Boeing 747 in terms of passenger capacity, with a maximum of 853.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Though development of this aircraft began in 1988 as a competitor to the 747, the A380 made its first test flight in April 2005.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The basis of most of these elements lies in theoretical physics, such as fluid dynamics for aerodynamics or the equations of motion for flight dynamics.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] There is also a large empirical component.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Historically, this empirical component was derived from testing of scale models and prototypes, either in wind tunnels or in the free atmosphere.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] More recently, advances in computing have enabled the use of computational fluid dynamics to simulate the behavior of the fluid, reducing time and expense spent on wind-tunnel testing.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Those studying hydrodynamics or hydroacoustics often obtain degrees in aerospace engineering.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Aerospace engineering may be studied at the advanced diploma, bachelor's, master's, and Ph.D. levels in aerospace engineering departments at many universities, and in mechanical engineering departments at others.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] A few departments offer degrees in space-focused astronautical engineering.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Some institutions differentiate between aeronautical and astronautical engineering.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Graduate degrees are offered in advanced or specialty areas for the aerospace industry.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] A background in chemistry, physics, computer science and mathematics is important for students pursuing an aerospace engineering degree.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The term "rocket scientist" is sometimes used to describe a person of great intelligence since rocket science is seen as a practice requiring great mental ability, especially technically and mathematically.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The term is used ironically in the expression "It's not rocket science" to indicate that a task is simple.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] Strictly speaking, the use of "science" in "rocket science" is a misnomer since science is about understanding the origins, nature, and behavior of the universe; engineering is about using scientific and engineering principles to solve problems and develop new technology.
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] The more etymologically correct version of this phrase would be "rocket engineer".
[src:genetic-engineering/aerospace-engineering] However, "science" and "engineering" are often misused as synonyms.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] An organism that is generated through genetic engineering is considered to be genetically modified (GM), and the resulting entity is a genetically modified organism (GMO).
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The first GMO was a bacterium generated by Herbert Boyer and Stanley Cohen in 1973.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Rudolf Jaenisch created the first GM animal when he inserted foreign DNA into a mouse in 1974.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The first company to focus on genetic engineering, Genentech, was founded in 1976 and began the production of human proteins.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetically engineered human insulin was produced in 1978, and insulin-producing bacteria were commercialised in 1982.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetically modified food has been sold since 1994, with the release of the Flavr Savr tomato.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The Flavr Savr was engineered to have a longer shelf life, but most current GM crops are modified to increase resistance to insects and herbicides.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] GloFish, the first GMO designed as a pet, was sold in the United States in December 2003.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 2016, salmon modified with a growth hormone were sold.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering has been applied in numerous fields, including research, medicine, industrial biotechnology, and agriculture.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In research, GMOs are used to study gene function and expression through loss-of-function, gain-of-function, tracking, and expression experiments.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] By knocking out genes responsible for certain conditions, it is possible to create animal model organisms of human diseases.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] As well as producing hormones, vaccines, and other drugs, genetic engineering has the potential to cure genetic diseases through gene therapy.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Chinese hamster ovary (CHO) cells are used in industrial genetic engineering.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Additionally, mRNA vaccines are made through genetic engineering to prevent infections by viruses such as COVID-19.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The same techniques that are used to produce drugs can also have industrial applications, such as producing enzymes for laundry detergent, cheeses, and other products.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The rise of commercialised genetically modified crops has provided economic benefit to farmers in many different countries; however, it has also been the source of most of the controversy surrounding the technology.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] This has been present since its early use; the first field trials were destroyed by anti-GM activists.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Although there is a scientific consensus that food derived from GMO crops poses no greater risk to human health than conventional food, after testing on a case by case basis, critics consider GM food safety a leading concern.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Gene flow, impact on non-target organisms, control of the food supply, and intellectual property rights have also been raised as potential issues.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] These concerns have led to the development of a regulatory framework, which started in 1975.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Eventually, this has led to a proposal of an international treaty, the Cartagena Protocol on Biosafety, which was officially adopted in 2000.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Individual countries have developed their own regulatory systems regarding GMOs, with the most marked differences occurring between the United States and Europe.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering is a process that alters the genetic structure of an organism by either removing or introducing DNA or modifying existing genetic material in situ.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Unlike traditional animal and plant breeding, which involves doing multiple crosses and then selecting for the organism with the desired phenotype, genetic engineering takes the gene directly from one organism and delivers it to the other.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] This is much faster, can be used to insert any genes from any organism (even ones from different domains), and prevents other undesirable genes from also being added.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering could potentially fix severe genetic disorders in humans by replacing the defective gene with a functioning one.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] It is an important tool in research that allows the function of specific genes to be studied.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Drugs, vaccines, and other products have been harvested from organisms engineered to produce them.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Crops have been developed that aid food security by increasing yield, nutritional value, and tolerance to environmental stresses.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The DNA can be introduced directly into the host organism or into a cell that is then fused or hybridised with the host.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] This relies on recombinant nucleic acid techniques to form new combinations of heritable genetic material, followed by the incorporation of that material either indirectly through a vector system or directly through micro-injection, macro-injection, or micro-encapsulation.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering does not normally include traditional breeding, in vitro fertilisation, induction of polyploidy, mutagenesis, and cell fusion techniques that do not use recombinant nucleic acids or a genetically modified organism in the process.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] However, some broad definitions of genetic engineering include selective breeding.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Cloning and stem cell research, although not considered genetic engineering, are closely related, and genetic engineering can be used within them.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Synthetic biology is an emerging discipline that takes genetic engineering a step further by introducing artificially synthesised material into an organism.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Plants, animals, or microorganisms that have been changed through genetic engineering are termed genetically modified organisms or GMOs.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] If genetic material from another species is added to the host, the resulting organism is called transgenic.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] If genetic material from the same species or a species that can naturally breed with the host is used, the resulting organism is called cisgenic.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] If genetic engineering is used to remove genetic material from the target organism, the resulting organism is termed a knockout organism.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In Europe, genetic modification is synonymous with genetic engineering while within the United States of America and Canada, genetic modification can also be used to refer to more conventional breeding methods.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Humans have altered the genomes of species for thousands of years through selective breeding, or artificial selection as contrasted with natural selection.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] More recently, mutation breeding has used exposure to chemicals or radiation to produce a high frequency of random mutations for selective breeding purposes.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering, as the direct manipulation of DNA by humans outside breeding and mutations, has only existed since the 1970s.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The term "genetic engineering" was coined by the Russian-born geneticist Nikolay Timofeev-Ressovsky in his 1934 paper "The Experimental Production of Mutations", published in the British journal Biological Reviews.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Weinbaum's 1936 science fiction story *Proteus Island*.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 1972, Paul Berg created the first recombinant DNA molecules by combining DNA from the monkey virus SV40 with that of the lambda virus.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 1973, Herbert Boyer and Stanley Cohen created the first transgenic organism by inserting antibiotic resistance genes into the plasmid of an *Escherichia coli* bacterium.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] One of the main recommendations from this meeting was that government oversight of recombinant DNA research should be established until the technology was deemed safe.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 1976, Genentech, the first genetic engineering company, was founded by Herbert Boyer and Robert Swanson and, a year later, the company produced a human protein (somatostatin) in *E. coli*.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genentech announced the production of genetically engineered human insulin in 1978.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 1980, the Supreme Court of the United States in the *Diamond v.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Chakrabarty* case ruled that genetically altered life could be patented.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The insulin produced by bacteria was approved for release by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in 1982.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 1987, the ice-minus strain of *P. syringae* became the first genetically modified organism (GMO) to be released into the environment when a strawberry field and a potato field in California were sprayed with it.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Both test fields were attacked by activist groups the night before the tests occurred: "The world's first trial site attracted the world's first field trasher".
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The first field trials of genetically engineered plants occurred in France and the US in 1986, and tobacco plants were engineered to be resistant to herbicides.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The People's Republic of China was the first country to commercialise transgenic plants, introducing a virus-resistant tobacco in 1992.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 1994, Calgene received official approval to commercially release the first genetically modified food, the Flavr Savr, a tomato engineered to have a longer shelf life.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 1994, the European Union approved tobacco engineered to be resistant to the herbicide bromoxynil, making it the first genetically engineered crop commercialised in Europe.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 1995, Bt potato was approved safe by the Environmental Protection Agency, after having been approved by the FDA, making it the first pesticide-producing crop to be approved in the US.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 2009, 11 transgenic crops were grown commercially in 25 countries, the largest of which by area grown were the United States, Brazil, Argentina, India, Canada, People's Republic of China, Paraguay, and South Africa.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Craig Venter Institute created the first synthetic genome and inserted it into an empty bacterial cell.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The resulting bacterium, named Mycoplasma laboratorium, could replicate and produce proteins.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Four years later, this was taken a step further when a bacterium was developed that replicated a plasmid containing a unique base pair, creating the first organism engineered to use an expanded genetic alphabet.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 2012, Jennifer Doudna and Emmanuelle Charpentier collaborated to develop the CRISPR/Cas9 system, a technique that can be used to easily and specifically alter the genome of almost any organism.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineers must first choose which gene they wish to insert into the organism.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] This is driven by what the aim is for the resultant organism and is built on earlier research.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic screens can be carried out to determine potential genes, and further tests can then be used to identify the most suitable candidates.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The development of microarrays, transcriptomics, and genome sequencing has made it much easier to find suitable genes.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Luck also plays its part; the Roundup Ready gene was discovered after scientists noticed a bacterium thriving in the presence of the herbicide.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The next step is to isolate the candidate gene.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The cell containing the gene is opened, and the DNA is purified.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The gene is separated by using restriction enzymes to cut the DNA into fragments or polymerase chain reaction (PCR) to amplify up the gene segment.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] These segments can then be extracted through gel electrophoresis.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] If the chosen gene or the donor organism's genome has been well studied, it may already be accessible from a genetic library.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] If the DNA sequence is known, but no copies of the gene are available, it can also be artificially synthesised.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Once isolated, the gene is ligated into a plasmid that is then inserted into a bacterium.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The plasmid is replicated when the bacteria divide, ensuring unlimited copies of the gene are available.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The RK2 plasmid is notable for its ability to replicate in a wide variety of single-celled organisms, which makes it suitable as a genetic engineering tool.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Before the gene is inserted into the target organism, it must be combined with other genetic elements.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] These include a promoter and terminator region, which initiate and end transcription.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] A selectable marker gene is added, which in most cases confers antibiotic resistance, so researchers can easily determine which cells have been successfully transformed.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The gene can also be modified at this stage for better expression or effectiveness.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] These manipulations are carried out using recombinant DNA techniques, such as restriction digests, ligations, and molecular cloning.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] There are a number of techniques used to insert genetic material into the host genome.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Some bacteria can naturally take up foreign DNA.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] This ability can be induced in other bacteria via stress (e.g., thermal or electric shock), which increases the cell membrane's permeability to DNA; up-taken DNA can either integrate with the genome or exist as extrachromosomal DNA.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] DNA is generally inserted into animal cells using microinjection, where it can be injected through the cell's nuclear envelope directly into the nucleus, or through the use of viral vectors.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Plant genomes can be engineered by physical methods or by the use of *Agrobacterium* for the delivery of sequences hosted in T-DNA binary vectors.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In plants, the DNA is often inserted using *Agrobacterium*-mediated transformation, taking advantage of the *Agrobacterium*s T-DNA sequence that allows natural insertion of genetic material into plant cells.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Other methods include biolistics, where particles of gold or tungsten are coated with DNA and then shot into young plant cells, and electroporation, which involves using an electric shock to make the cell membrane permeable to plasmid DNA.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] As only a single cell is transformed with genetic material, the organism must be regenerated from that single cell.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In plants, this is accomplished through the use of tissue culture.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In animals, it is necessary to ensure that the inserted DNA is present in the embryonic stem cells.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Bacteria consist of a single cell and reproduce clonally, so regeneration is not necessary.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Selectable markers are used to easily differentiate transformed from untransformed cells.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] These markers are usually present in the transgenic organism, although a number of strategies have been developed that can remove the selectable marker from the mature transgenic plant.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Further testing using PCR, Southern hybridization, and DNA sequencing is conducted to confirm that an organism contains the new gene.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] These tests can also confirm the chromosomal location and copy number of the inserted gene.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The presence of the gene does not guarantee it will be expressed at appropriate levels in the target tissue so methods that look for and measure the gene products (RNA and protein) are also used.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] These include northern hybridisation, quantitative RT-PCR, Western blot, immunofluorescence, ELISA, and phenotypic analysis.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The new genetic material can be inserted randomly within the host genome or targeted to a specific location.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The technique of gene targeting uses homologous recombination to make desired changes to a specific endogenous gene.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] This tends to occur at a relatively low frequency in plants and animals and generally requires the use of selectable markers.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The frequency of gene targeting can be greatly enhanced through genome editing.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genome editing utilizes artificially engineered nucleases that create specific double-stranded breaks at desired locations in the genome, and use the cell's endogenous mechanisms to repair the induced break by the natural processes of homologous recombination and nonhomologous end-joining.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] There are four families of engineered nucleases: meganucleases, zinc finger nucleases, transcription activator-like effector nucleases (TALENs), and the Cas9-guideRNA system (adapted from CRISPR).
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] TALEN and CRISPR are the two most commonly used, and each has its own advantages.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] TALENs have greater target specificity, while CRISPR is easier to design and more efficient.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In addition to enhancing gene targeting, engineered nucleases can be used to introduce mutations at endogenous genes that generate a gene knockout.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering has applications in medicine, research, industry, and agriculture, and can be used on a wide range of plants, animals, and microorganisms.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Bacteria, the first organisms to be genetically modified, can have plasmid DNA inserted containing new genes that code for medicines or enzymes that process food and other substrates.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Plants have been modified for insect protection, herbicide resistance, virus resistance, enhanced nutrition, tolerance to environmental pressures, and the production of edible vaccines.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Most commercialised GMOs are insect-resistant or herbicide-tolerant crop plants.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetically modified animals have been used for research, model animals, and the production of agricultural or pharmaceutical products.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The genetically modified animals include animals with genes knocked out, increased susceptibility to disease, hormones for extra growth, and the ability to express proteins in their milk.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering has many applications to medicine that include the manufacturing of drugs, the creation of model animals that mimic human conditions, and gene therapy.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] One of the earliest uses of genetic engineering was to mass-produce human insulin in bacteria.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] This application has now been applied to human growth hormones, follicle-stimulating hormones (for treating infertility), human albumin, monoclonal antibodies, antihemophilic factors, vaccines, and many other drugs.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Mouse hybridomas, cells fused together to create monoclonal antibodies, have been adapted through genetic engineering to create human monoclonal antibodies.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetically engineered viruses are being developed that can still confer immunity, but lack the infectious sequences.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering is also used to create animal models of human diseases.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetically modified mice are the most common genetically engineered animal model.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] They have been used to study and model cancer (the oncomouse), obesity, heart disease, diabetes, arthritis, substance abuse, anxiety, aging, and Parkinson's disease.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Potential cures can be tested against these mouse models.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Gene therapy is the genetic engineering of humans, generally by replacing defective genes with effective ones.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Clinical research using somatic gene therapy has been conducted with several diseases, including X-linked SCID, chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL), and Parkinson's disease.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 2012, Alipogene tiparvovec became the first gene therapy treatment to be approved for clinical use.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 2015, a virus was used to insert a healthy gene into the skin cells of a boy suffering from a rare skin disease, epidermolysis bullosa, in order to grow, and then graft healthy skin onto 80 percent of the boy's body, which was affected by the illness.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Germline gene therapy would result in any change being inheritable, which has raised concerns within the scientific community.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 2015, CRISPR was used to edit the DNA of non-viable human embryos, leading scientists of major world academies to call for a moratorium on inheritable human genome edits.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] There are also concerns that the technology could be used not just for treatment, but for enhancement, modification, or alteration of a human beings' appearance, adaptability, intelligence, character, or behavior.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The distinction between cure and enhancement can also be difficult to establish.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In November 2018, He Jiankui announced that he had edited the genomes of two human embryos, to attempt to disable the *CCR5* gene, which codes for a receptor that HIV uses to enter cells.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The work was widely condemned as unethical, dangerous, and premature.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Currently, germline modification is banned in 40 countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Scientists who perform this type of research will often let embryos grow for a few days without allowing them to develop into a baby.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Researchers are altering the genome of pigs to induce the growth of human organs, with the aim of increasing the success of pig-to-human organ transplantation.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Scientists are creating "gene drives", changing the genomes of mosquitoes to make them immune to malaria, and then looking to spread the genetically altered mosquitoes throughout the mosquito population in the hopes of eliminating the disease.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering is an important tool for natural scientists, with the creation of transgenic organisms one of the most important tools for the analysis of gene function.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genes and other genetic information from a wide range of organisms can be inserted into bacteria for storage and modification, creating genetically modified bacteria in the process .
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Bacteria are cheap, easy to grow, clonal, multiply quickly, relatively easy to transform, and can be stored at -80 °C almost indefinitely.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Once a gene is isolated, it can be stored inside the bacteria, providing an unlimited supply for research.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Organisms are genetically engineered to discover the functions of certain genes.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] This could be the effect on the phenotype of the organism, where the gene is expressed or what other genes it interacts with.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] These experiments generally involve loss of function, gain of function, tracking, and expression.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Organisms can have their cells transformed with a gene coding for a useful protein, such as an enzyme, so that they will overexpress the desired protein.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Mass quantities of the protein can then be manufactured by growing the transformed organism in bioreactor equipment using industrial fermentation, and then purifying the protein.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Some genes do not work well in bacteria, so yeast, insect cells or mammalian cells can also be used.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] These techniques are used to produce medicines such as insulin, human growth hormone, and vaccines, supplements such as tryptophan, aid in the production of food (chymosin in cheese making) and fuels.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Other applications with genetically engineered bacteria could involve making them perform tasks outside their natural cycle, such as making biofuels, cleaning up oil spills, carbon and other toxic waste and detecting arsenic in drinking water.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Certain genetically modified microbes can also be used in biomining and bioremediation, due to their ability to extract heavy metals from their environment and incorporate them into compounds that are more easily recoverable.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In materials science, a genetically modified virus has been used in a research laboratory as a scaffold for assembling a more environmentally friendly lithium-ion battery.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Bacteria have also been engineered to function as sensors by expressing a fluorescent protein under certain environmental conditions.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] One of the best-known and controversial applications of genetic engineering is the creation and use of genetically modified crops or genetically modified livestock to produce genetically modified food.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Crops have been developed to increase production, increase tolerance to abiotic stresses, alter the composition of the food, or to produce novel products.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The first crops to be released commercially on a large scale provided protection from insect pests or tolerance to herbicides.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Fungal and virus resistant crops have also been developed or are in development.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] This makes the insect and weed management of crops easier and can indirectly increase crop yield.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] GM crops that directly improve yield by accelerating growth or making the plant more hardy (by improving salt, cold or drought tolerance) are also under development.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In 2016 Salmon have been genetically modified with growth hormones to reach normal adult size much faster.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] GMOs have been developed that modify the quality of produce by increasing the nutritional value or providing more industrially useful qualities or quantities.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The Amflora potato produces a more industrially useful blend of starches.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Soybeans and canola have been genetically modified to produce more healthy oils.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The first commercialised GM food was a tomato that had delayed ripening, increasing its shelf life.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Plants and animals have been engineered to produce materials they do not normally make.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Pharming uses crops and animals as bioreactors to produce vaccines, drug intermediates, or the drugs themselves; the useful product is purified from the harvest and then used in the standard pharmaceutical production process.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Cows and goats have been engineered to express drugs and other proteins in their milk, and in 2009 the FDA approved a drug produced in goat milk.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering has potential applications in conservation and natural area management.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Gene transfer through viral vectors has been proposed as a means of controlling invasive species as well as vaccinating threatened fauna from disease.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Transgenic trees have been suggested as a way to confer resistance to pathogens in wild populations.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] With the increasing risks of maladaptation in organisms as a result of climate change and other perturbations, facilitated adaptation through gene tweaking could be one solution to reducing extinction risks.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Applications of genetic engineering in conservation are thus far mostly theoretical and have yet to be put into practice.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering is also being used to create microbial art.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Some bacteria have been genetically engineered to create black and white photographs.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Novelty items such as lavender-colored carnations, blue roses, and glowing fish, have also been produced through genetic engineering.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The regulation of genetic engineering concerns the approaches taken by governments to assess and manage the risks associated with the development and release of GMOs.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The development of a regulatory framework began in 1975, at Asilomar, California.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The Asilomar meeting recommended a set of voluntary guidelines regarding the use of recombinant technology.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] As the technology improved the US established a committee at the Office of Science and Technology, which assigned regulatory approval of GM food to the USDA, FDA and EPA.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The Cartagena Protocol on Biosafety, an international treaty that governs the transfer, handling, and use of GMOs, was adopted on 29 January 2000.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] One hundred and fifty-seven countries are members of the Protocol, and many use it as a reference point for their own regulations.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The legal and regulatory status of GM foods varies by country, with some nations banning or restricting them, and others permitting them with widely differing degrees of regulation.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Some countries allow the import of GM food with authorisation, but either do not allow its cultivation (Russia, Norway, Israel) or have provisions for cultivation even though no GM products are yet produced (Japan, South Korea).
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Most countries that do not allow GMO cultivation do permit research.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Some of the most marked differences occur between the US and Europe.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The US policy focuses on the product (not the process), only looks at verifiable scientific risks and uses the concept of substantial equivalence.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The European Union by contrast has possibly the most stringent GMO regulations in the world.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] All GMOs, along with irradiated food, are considered "new food" and subject to extensive, case-by-case, science-based food evaluation by the European Food Safety Authority.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The criteria for authorisation fall in four broad categories: "safety", "freedom of choice", "labelling", and "traceability".
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The level of regulation in other countries that cultivate GMOs lie in between Europe and the United States.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] One of the key issues concerning regulators is whether GM products should be labeled.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The European Commission says that mandatory labeling and traceability are needed to allow for informed choice, avoid potential false advertising and facilitate the withdrawal of products if adverse effects on health or the environment are discovered.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] The American Medical Association and the American Association for the Advancement of Science say that absent scientific evidence of harm even voluntary labeling is misleading and will falsely alarm consumers.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Labeling of GMO products in the marketplace is required in 64 countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Labeling can be mandatory up to a threshold GM content level (which varies between countries) or voluntary.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In Canada and the US labeling of GM food is voluntary, while in Europe all food (including processed food) or feed which contains greater than 0.9% of approved GMOs must be labelled.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Critics have objected to the use of genetic engineering on several grounds, including ethical, ecological and economic concerns.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Many of these concerns involve GM crops and whether food produced from them is safe and what impact growing them will have on the environment.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] These controversies have led to litigation, international trade disputes, and protests, and to restrictive regulation of commercial products in some countries.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Accusations that scientists are "playing God" and other religious issues have been ascribed to the technology from the beginning.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Other ethical issues raised include the patenting of life, the use of intellectual property rights, the level of labeling on products, control of the food supply and the objectivity of the regulatory process.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Although doubts have been raised, economically most studies have found growing GM crops to be beneficial to farmers.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Gene flow between GM crops and compatible plants, along with increased use of selective herbicides, can increase the risk of "superweeds" developing.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Other environmental concerns involve potential impacts on non-target organisms, including soil microbes, and an increase in secondary and resistant insect pests.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Many of the environmental impacts regarding GM crops may take many years to be understood and are also evident in conventional agriculture practices.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] With the commercialisation of genetically modified fish there are concerns over what the environmental consequences will be if they escape.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] There are three main concerns over the safety of genetically modified food: whether they may provoke an allergic reaction; whether the genes could transfer from the food into human cells; and whether the genes not approved for human consumption could outcross to other crops.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] There is a scientific consensus that currently available food derived from GM crops poses no greater risk to human health than conventional food, but that each GM food needs to be tested on a case-by-case basis before introduction.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Nonetheless, members of the public are less likely than scientists to perceive GM foods as safe.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering features in many science fiction stories.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Frank Herbert's novel *The White Plague* describes the deliberate use of genetic engineering to create a pathogen which specifically kills women.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Another of Herbert's creations, the *Dune* series of novels, uses genetic engineering to create the powerful Tleilaxu.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Few films have informed audiences about genetic engineering, with the exception of the 1978 *The Boys from Brazil* and the 1993 *Jurassic Park*, both of which make use of a lesson, a demonstration, and a clip of scientific film.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] Genetic engineering methods are weakly represented in film; Michael Clark, writing for the Wellcome Trust, calls the portrayal of genetic engineering and biotechnology "seriously distorted" in films such as *The 6th Day*.
[src:genetic-engineering/genetic-engineering] In Clark's view, the biotechnology is typically "given fantastic but visually arresting forms" while the science is either relegated to the background or fictionalised to suit a young audience.
